# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1907-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The **1907 Detroit Tigers** won the American League pennant with a record of 92–58, but lost to the Chicago Cubs in the 1907 World Series, four games to none (with one tie).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The season was their seventh since they entered the American League in 1901.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In March 1907, Detroit manager Hughie Jennings actually offered Ty Cobb to the Cleveland Naps in exchange for Elmer Flick.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The 1907 season was the first year the Tigers won the American League pennant.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Their 1907 record of 92–58 was the team's best record to that point.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] They finished 1½ games ahead of the A's.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Athletics and Detroit Tigers vied for the pennant through the 1907 season.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers came into Philadelphia for a three game series on September 27, 1907 in a virtual tie for first-place.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit took the first game 5-4 to move in front of an official attendance of 17,926, exceeding Columbia Park's capacity.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Saturday's game was postponed by rain, and Pennsylvania Blue Laws precluded play on Sunday.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] A double-header was scheduled for Monday.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's Bill Donovan had pitched a complete game in the Friday game and was slated to start both games of the double-header.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] With a week left in the season, Athletics fans were eager to see the team capture the pennant.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] It was estimated that the team could have sold 50,000 tickets to the Monday double-header.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] With Columbia Park's limited capacity, an overflow crowd spilled into a roped-off area on the outfield grass.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The gates were locked 30 minutes before game time with thousands of fans outside unable to gain admittance.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Fans stormed the gates and climbed over the outside fence, with more than the official 24,127 seeing the game.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The *Philadelphia Inquirer* would remark on the crowd, "Never before in the history of the national game has so great and remarkable a gathering of its enthusiastic followers been held anywhere." Fans scaled trolley and telegraph poles to watch the game.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Local residents charged as much as $1 to $5 a person ($35 to $125 in 2025-dollars) to watch the game from windows.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] On the Twenty-ninth street side of the park, a fan in the grandstand lowered a rope up which fans scrambled from the street and into the park.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Large men charged ten-cents to boost fans over the fence and into the park.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Down by six in the fifth, the Tigers came into the ninth down 8-6.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Sam Crawford opened the ninth with a single off of future Hall of Fame Rube Waddell bringing 20-year year old Ty Cobb to the plate.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Cobb crushed Waddell's pitch, clearing the right-field fence by fifty-feet and onto 29th Street for a game-tying homerun.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The teams both scored in the eleventh and would battle to a 9-9 tie in 17-innings before darkness ended the game.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The *Philadelphia Inquirer* would call it "the most remarkable game ever played on the Athletic ground." Reflecting on his career in 1930, Cobb would tell Grantland Rice, "The biggest thrill I ever got came in a game was against the Athletics in 1907 [on September 30]...
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Athletics had us beaten, with Rube Waddell pitching.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] They were two runs ahead in the 9th inning, when I happened to hit a home run that tied the score.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] This game went 17 innings to a tie, and a few days later, we clinched our first pennant.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Catching duties were split between Boss Schmidt (67 games), Fred Payne (46 games), and Jimmy Archer (17 games).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] As a young man, Schmidt worked in the coal mines and was a skilled brawler who fought an exhibition match with the heavyweight champion, Jack Johnson.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Schmidt also beat Ty Cobb in at least two fights.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In the second fight, Schmidt knocked Cobb unconscious but admired Cobb's resiliency, and the two became friends until Schmidt's death in 1932.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Schmidt never wore shinguards and could force nails into the floor with his bare fists.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman Claude Rossman played for the Tigers from 1907 to 1909.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In 1907, Rossman hit .277 and had 69 RBIs—third most on the team after Cobb and Crawford.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Rossman had a peculiar emotional quirk where he sometimes froze and could not throw the ball when he became excited.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Runners would lead off first to draw a throw from the pitcher, then run to second when Rossman froze.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He was 28 when he played his last major league game and died at age 46 in a New York hospital for the insane where he had been a patient for several years.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Red Downs and Germany Schaefer platooned at the second base position for the Tigers in 1907 and 1908.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Downs hit .219 in 1907 with 42 RBIs and 28 runs scored.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In March 1932, Downs and another man robbed a jewelry store at the Biltmore Hotel in Los Angeles.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Downs was convicted of first-degree robbery and sentenced to five years to life.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He was paroled after 3½ years and returned to Iowa.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Germany Schaefer was a backup second baseman and utility infielder for the 1907 Tigers.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He played 74 games at second base, 18 at shortstop, and 14 at third base.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Schaefer is remembered more for his antics than for his performance on the field, including trying to steal first base (from second base) and, coming to bat in the rain with a raincoat and boots (to persuade the umpire to call the games).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Schaefer was a pioneer of baseball clowning, and his vaudeville act with teammate Charley O'Leary was inspiration for the MGM musical film "*Take Me Out To The Ball Game*" starring Gene Kelly and Frank Sinatra.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In 1919, a little over a year after Schaefer played his last game, he died at age 42 of tuberculosis at the sanitarium in Saranac Lake, New York.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Charley O'Leary was Detroit's starting shortstop from 1904 to 1907.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] On September 30, 1934, O'Leary pinch hit for the St.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Louis Browns at age 51 and became one of the oldest players to collect a hit and score a run.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Third baseman Bill Coughlin, known as "Scranton Bill", was named team captain in 1907 and 1908.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He was a light-hitting defensive player, who never hit higher than .252 for the Tigers.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] His 232 putouts in 1901 is the 8th highest single season total in history by a major league third baseman.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He is also one of the few MLB players to have stolen 2nd base, 3rd base and home in a single game.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Coughlin was also the maestro of the hidden ball trick.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Although no known comprehensive list is known to exist of all times when the hidden ball trick has worked, Coughlin reportedly pulled it off seven times (and at three different positions) – more than any other player in MLB history.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 2 of the 1907 World Series, Coughlin caught Jimmy Slagle with a hidden ball trick, the only one in World Series history.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] 1907 was Ty Cobb's first season as an every-day starter.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He won his first batting crown with a .350 average and led the American League in RBIs (119), slugging percentage (.468), hits (212), total bases (283), stolen bases (49), and runs created (106).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Right fielder Sam Crawford, known as "Wahoo Sam", was one of the greatest sluggers of the deadball era and still holds the major league records for triples in a career (309) and for inside-the-park home runs in a season (12) and a career (51).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He finished his career with 2,961 hits and a .309 batting average.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Crawford was among the AL leaders in hits, RBIs, extra base hits, slugging percentage, and total bases every year for twelve consecutive years from 1905 to 1915.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In 1907, Crawford finished second in the AL in batting average (.323) behind Cobb, and led the league in runs scored (102) and extra base hits.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Davy Jones played for the Tigers from 1906 to 1912.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] With Cobb and Crawford solidly entrenched in the outfield, Jones was forced to battle for the third outfield spot with Matty McIntyre each year from 1906 to 1910.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] As a speedy leadoff man, he was a reliable run scorer with Cobb and Crawford following him in the lineup.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Jones' speed also made him a fine outfielder, with tremendous range In 1907, he finished second in the AL with 101 runs.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In his three World Series for the Tigers, Jones played in 18 games, had a .357 on-base percentage, scored 8 runs, and had a home run in the 1909 World Series against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] "Wild Bill" Donovan was the Tigers ace in 1907 with a 25–4 record—the best win percentage in Tigers' team history.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] On May 7, 1906, Donovan stole second base, third base, and home on the front end of a double steal and also hit a triple in the same game.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In June 1923, Donovan died in a train wreck.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Ed Killian led the team (and was 2nd in the AL) with a 1.78 ERA and compiled a 25–13 record.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] As of the end of the 2009 season, Killian's career ERA of 2.38 is the 26th-best in MLB history.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Killian also holds the record for fewest home runs allowed, giving up only 9 in his entire career.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] At one point, Killian pitched a record 1001 innings (from September 1903 – August 1907) without allowing a home run.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] George Mullin won 20 games in 1907, but he also lost 20 games.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] His ERA of 2.59 was the highest among the four Detroit starting pitchers.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Mullin holds the Detroit Tigers franchise record for innings pitched (in a career and in a season) and has the second most wins in the team's history.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] He also pitched the team's first no-hitter; had five 20-win seasons (including a league-leading 29 wins in 1909; twice hit over .310 as a batter); and ranks 7th in major league history for fielding assists by a pitcher.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The fourth Tiger starter was Ed Siever who had a 2.16 ERA in 1907 with a record of 18–11.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Siever's Adjusted ERA+ of 191 for the 1902 Tigers is the second-best (after Hal Newhouser) in Tigers franchise history for a pitcher with more than 150 innings pitched.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] (See Detroit Tigers award winners and league leaders) Ironically, Siever won fewer games in 1902 than he did any other full season he played.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Hughie "Ee-yah" Jennings led the Tigers to three consecutive American League pennants, in 1907–08–09.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Jennings continued to manage the Tigers through the 1920 season, though his team never won another pennant.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] During his years as Detroit's manager, Jennings became famous for his antics, mostly in the third base coaching box, which variously included shouts of "Ee-Yah", and other whoops, whistles, horns, gyrations, jigs, and grass-plucking.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The "Ee-Yah" whoop became his trademark and was accompanied with waves of both arms over his head and a sharp raising of his right knee.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In 1907, he was suspended for taunting opponents with a tin whistle.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The "Ee-Yah" shouts continued and became such a trademark that Jennings became known as Hughie "Ee-Yah" Jennings, and Detroit fans would shout "Ee-Yah" when Jennings would appear on the field.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] According to Connie Mack (a fellow baseball manager), Jennings was one of the three greatest managers in history, along with John McGraw and Joe McCarthy.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In the 1907 World Series, the Chicago Cubs beat the Tigers 4 games to none (with one tie).
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] With pitching dominance over the Tigers and Cobb, the Cubs allowed only three runs in the four games they won, while stealing 18 bases off the rattled Tigers.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 1, Tigers pitcher Bill Donovan struck out twelve Cubs in 12 innings.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers scored three runs, in part due to three Chicago errors, in the 8th inning and held a 3–1 lead going into the bottom of the 9th.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Cubs loaded the bases on a single, walk and infield error with one out.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit conceded a run on a ground ball for the second out and Cub player-manager Frank Chance then used pinch-hitter Del Howard to bat for Joe Tinker.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Howard struck out against "Wild" Bill Donovan (25–4 in the regular season) but the ball got away from catcher Boss Schmidt, allowing Harry Steinfeldt to score the tying run.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Donovan got the next batter but the damage to Detroit has been done.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The teams then played three scoreless innings before the game was called on account of darkness and declared a tie, a first for the World Series.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 2, George Mullin, a 20-game winner and loser for Detroit in 1907 and who had walked over 100 batters in each of his last five seasons, issues a bases-loaded walk in the 2nd inning to tie the game at 1–1.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Chicago scored two more in the 4th on a single, sacrifice bunt, RBI single, stolen base and double to take a 3–1 lead.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, Cubs pitcher Ed Reulbach scattered six hits as Chicago jumped on Tiger starter Ed Siever for four runs on seven hits in only four innings.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Johnny Evers had three hits, including two doubles, as the Cubs took a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 4, Detroit held a 1–0 lead on a triple by Ty Cobb and an RBI single by Claude Rossman before a rain delay in the 5th inning.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] When play resumed, Chicago baserunners reached via an error and a walk.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] After Joe Tinker sacrificed, pitcher Orval Overall drove both runners home on a single to right field.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Cubs scored three more in the 7th without hitting the ball out of the infield on four bunts (two for hits) and two ground balls.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 5, Chicago wrapped up the series with a 2–0 victory as Mordecai Brown pitched a seven-hit shutout.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] The Cubs scored a run in the first inning on a walk, stolen base and RBI single by Harry Steinfeldt and scored again in the 2nd on an error, a single, a double-steal and a ground ball out to drive in the final run.
[src:1907-detroit-tigers-season/1907-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit had runners on 2nd and 3rd with one out in the 4th inning, but could not score and never seriously threatened after that.
